      en: "Artistâ€™s Statement about this Painting This painting feels like the skin of the earth â€” wounded, alive, and eternal The cracked lines are like ancient veins, carrying memories buried beneath centuries of silence. The deep green color hums quietly, like a forest that once burned but still breathes beneath the ashes. From afar, it may look like a wall â€” strong, unyielding â€” but as you come closer, you realize itâ€™s not a wall at all. Itâ€™s skin. The skin of the earth, of the soul, of a human who has endured time itself. Every fracture is a border between what was and what remains, between what weâ€™ve lost and what still breathes somewhere inside us. There is no perfect geometry here. The lines move freely, like life itself â€” unpredictable, scarred, yet full of rhythm. It feels as if the ground is whispering its own story, not with words, but with silence, texture, and breath. Look closely, and youâ€™ll see a faint light running through the cracks â€” a quiet symbol of hope pushing through the darkness. That tension â€” between weight and grace, damage and renewal â€” is what keeps the painting alive. This artwork is a confession: even in decay, there is beauty. The beauty of endurance. Thatâ€™s why your eyes come back again and again â€” to find something new each time, something that speaks without shouting, that feels without asking. Each viewer discovers a different map within these lines â€” one sees pain, another patience, another history, and someone else only stillness. But no one walks away untouched. Because somewhere in this cracked surface lies a truth we all share: we are all scarred, yet we remain. This painting may look like stone, but itâ€™s truly a portrait of humanity â€” broken, yet standing. And that, more than anything, is what makes it alive." 
